2] Issue while doing a git push even your key has been added to the Github.

	# git push
	Username for 'https://github.com': ******
	Password for 'https://******@github.com':
	remote: Invalid username or token. Password authentication is not supported for Git operations.
	fatal: Authentication failed for 'https://github.com/******/DevopsJourney.git/'

		Your GitHub login password is not valid for git push over HTTPS. 
		GitHub only allows Git over HTTPS with a personal access token (PAT), or Git over SSH with an SSH key. 
		That is why GitHub is prompting for a username and password and then rejecting it with Invalid username or token. 
		Password authentication is not supported for Git operations.
	
		In your case, you already created an SSH key and added it to GitHub, but your local repository is still using an HTTPS remote URL.
		And not an SSH remote URL. That is why git push is asking for Username for 'https://github.com' instead of using your SSH key.
	
		GitHub’s docs show that remotes can use either an HTTPS URL like,
		https://github.com/OWNER/REPO.git or an SSH URL like git@github.com:OWNER/REPO.git, 
		and you can switch between them with "git remote set-url"
	
			1] Check what remote you currently have
				# git remote -v
			
			2] If it is https, it is self explonatory.
			3] Change it to SSH 
				# git remote set-url origin git@github.com:<yourUsername>/DevopsJourney.git
			
			4] Verify it using "git remote -v"
			5] Now you will be able to do push using ssh.
				# git push -u origin main
			OR 
				# git push -u origin master
	
		- Now if you want to use the https as your original method.
			- You will need to create a Token first.
			- https://github.com/settings/tokens
			- Create a new token classic.
			- add expiration and then uise repo for full control.
			- Generate and copy the token.
			- use that token while login.
